.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:158:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:159:## 3. SURFACE STANDARDS (the non-negotiables)
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:160:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:161:- **Plugins never write to the TUI.** OpenCode plugins must not print to the process stdout/stderr (no overlay on the chat input); user/agent-visible output goes through system-context injection, tools, or append-only log files; DEBUG-gated stderr is allowed only behind an env flag. See `references/javascript/quality-standards/overview-modules-and-docs.md` and the plugin exemption tier.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:162:- **Descriptors are load-bearing.** `graph-metadata.json` / `description.json` shape drives discovery; validate JSON/JSONC against `references/config/quality-standards.md`.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:163:- **Alignment drift is a verification gate.** System-code changes re-run the alignment verifier (`references/shared/alignment-verification-automation.md`) before any completion claim.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:164:- **Rust preserves the TypeScript contract.** Rust napi-rs, WASM/WASI, and sidecar modules are compatibility implementations, not independent behavior authorities. JS-visible bytes, six-decimal numeric behavior, comparator tie-breaks, deterministic IDs, collection order, DTOs, and error shapes must remain identical to the TypeScript oracle.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:165:- **Touched-language set, not one-per-task.** Most `.opencode/` tasks touch a single language — keep that slice tight and lean on the shared tier for cross-language rules. An interop task that spans a language pair (a napi-rs / WASM / sidecar Rust module held to its TypeScript oracle) legitimately touches both languages: the router slices to the set the task actually touches and loads both trios plus the shared tier, because you cannot hold Rust byte-identical to TypeScript without seeing both standards.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:166:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:167:## 4. ASSETS AND OTHER SURFACE AREAS — on-demand
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:168:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:169:Component authoring (`assets/checklists/`): `skill-authoring.md`, `agent-authoring.md`, `command-authoring.md`, `mcp-server-authoring.md`
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:170:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:171:Language quality gates (`assets/checklists/`): `universal-checklist.md`, `typescript-checklist.md`, `python-checklist.md`, `shell-checklist.md`, `javascript-checklist.md`, `rust-checklist/` (split into topic parts), `config-checklist.md`
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:172:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:173:Verifier assets (`assets/scripts/`): alignment-drift and stack-folder verifier scripts used by this surface.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:174:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:175:Changelog directories (`changelog/`): real skill and packet changelog files are part of the OpenCode surface inventory, not out-of-scope documentation noise.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:176:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:177:Daemon IPC/socket wiring: daemon-backed CLIs and plugin bridges resolve runtime Unix socket paths such as `daemon-ipc.sock`; sockets are runtime artifacts, so checked-in evidence lives in launcher, bridge, and config files rather than in committed `.sock` files.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:178:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-opencode/SKILL.md:179:Spec-folder authoring lives in system-spec-kit (`references/workflows/spec-folder-write-recipe.md` + `spec-folder-authoring-checklist.md`), not in this surface. Checklists are pulled on demand by the active workflow phase.

