     7	
     8	<!-- Keywords: create-benchmark, benchmark-report.md, source.md, mcp_server benchmarks, benchmark promotion, skill-local benchmark, MCP bake-off, benchmark folder, behavior benchmark, behavior-benchmark.md, behavior_benchmark, conformance benchmark, conformance_benchmark, peer adapter benchmark, deep-alignment benchmark, lane-config benchmark, sk-doc-command, scenario contract, DAB scenario, behavior-benchmark framework, claude-baseline, skill-benchmark, benchmark/README.md, run-label folder, skill-benchmark-report, Lane C benchmark, model-benchmark, benchmark fixture, benchmark profile, code-task oracle fixture, reviewer-prompt fixture, Lane B fixture, command benchmark, command-benchmark, command surface benchmark, command benchmark matrix -->
     9	
    10	# create-benchmark
    11	
    12	`create-benchmark` is the benchmark-authoring workflow packet of the `sk-doc` family. It authors four benchmark families plus MCP-promotion artifacts, and provides an authoring guide for one more lane that stays code-owned:
    13	
    14	- **MCP promotion benchmark** — turn a shipped spec packet's curated benchmark evidence into a consuming skill's `mcp-server/benchmarks/benchmark-<YYYY-MM-DD>/` folder, so MCP operators can find the winner, fixture, caveats, replay commands, and source packet without leaving the skill tree (sections 3 through 8).
    15	- **Behavior benchmark** — author a `<mode>/behavior-benchmark/` package (index, per-scenario machine contracts, and a Claude baseline) that specifies executor-model behavior at a deep-loop mode's invocation surface, governed by the shared measurement framework (section 9).
    16	- **Conformance benchmark** — author a `<mode>/assets/conformance-benchmark/<benchmark-id>/` input package for deterministic artifact-conformance checks through a deep-alignment peer adapter, without running the adapter or benchmark (section 12).
    17	- **Skill-benchmark (Lane C)** — author a hub's `benchmark/` storage tree and its `benchmark/README.md` run-label index; the per-run `skill-benchmark-report.md` is a renderer-owned render this packet never authors (section 10).
    18	- **Model-benchmark (Lane B)** — author the Lane B input fixtures (code-task oracle, pattern/capability, reviewer-prompt) and the run profiles; the evaluator, scorers, and reviewer-verdict contract stay lane-local (section 11).
    19	
    20	Lane A (agent-improvement) carries an authoring guide here (section 14); artifacts stay code-owned in-lane.
    21	
    22	The skill-local surface is the look-here-first entry point, not the archive.
    23	
    24	---
    25	
    26	## 1. WHEN TO USE
    27	
    28	Use this packet when a completed benchmark, or a benchmark's input artifacts, needs to be authored into the skill tree as durable, look-here-first documentation. Settle which family applies via the router in section 2 first — families are distinct and must not be conflated.
    29	
    30	### Activation Triggers
    31	
    32	- **MCP promotion** (on-disk `shared`; sections 3-8) — promote a completed MCP benchmark or bake-off from a spec packet into a skill-local `mcp-server/benchmarks/` folder: author the ten-section `benchmark-report.md` and `source.md`, copy `results.csv` / `per-probe.jsonl` / runtime sidecars into a dated folder, and update the `benchmarks/README.md` index row.
    33	- **Behavior benchmark** (section 9) — author or extend a `behavior-benchmark` package for a deep-loop mode. The framework fixes an ID prefix per package — `research` (RSB), `review` (RVB), `ai-council` (ACB), `improvement` (IMB), and `alignment` (DAB) — and a new mode extends that table with its own prefix declared in the index OVERVIEW: the `behavior-benchmark.md` index, per-scenario `<PREFIX>-NNN-<slug>.md` machine contracts, and `baselines/claude-baseline.md`, designing the entry-surface and clarity scenario matrix.
    34	- **Conformance benchmark** (section 12) — author a deterministic `conformance-benchmark` input package for a peer-adapter or deep-alignment benchmark, including the family index, contract, lane config, and fixture manifest; routing aliases may retain the machine key `conformance_benchmark`.
    35	- **Skill-benchmark** (section 10) — author or update a hub's `benchmark/README.md` run-label index, or establish the `benchmark/` storage convention (sibling run-label folders, frozen `baseline/` anchor) for a Lane C tree.
    36	- **Model-benchmark** (section 11) — author a Lane B input fixture (code-task oracle, pattern/capability, or reviewer-prompt) or a run profile that selects fixtures, models, frameworks, scoring, and the gate.
    37	- **Lane A guide** (section 14) — author the Lane A (`agent_improvement`) authoring guide; rubrics, configs, and templates stay in-lane.
    38	
    39	Keyword triggers: `benchmark-report.md`, `source.md`, `mcp-server/benchmarks`, `MCP bake-off`; `behavior benchmark`, `behavior-benchmark.md`, `behavior_benchmark`, `scenario contract`, `claude-baseline`; `conformance benchmark`, `conformance_benchmark`, `peer adapter benchmark`, `deep-alignment benchmark`, `lane-config benchmark`, `sk-doc-command`; `skill-benchmark`, `benchmark/README.md`, `run-label folder`, `benchmark package`; `model-benchmark`, `benchmark fixture`, `benchmark profile`, `reviewer-prompt fixture`; `command benchmark`, `command-benchmark`, `command surface benchmark`, `command benchmark matrix`.
    40	
    41	### Adoption Gate (MCP promotion)
    42	
    43	Create a skill-local MCP-promotion benchmark folder only when all of the following hold:
    44	
    45	- The skill houses an MCP server under `mcp-server/`.
    46	- That server produces a measurable retrieval, quality, runtime, throughput, top-k recall, hit rate, latency, RAM, dim, or similar numeric outcome.
    47	- A benchmark run has already completed inside a spec packet.
    48	- The curated headline is worth promoting where operators read code.
    49	- The run has enough rigor that another author can replay it: stable fixture, replay commands, and expected outcome.
    50	- The source packet has accepted ADRs or an accepted decision record.
    51	
    52	Decision rule:
    53	
    54	```text
    55	Measurable retrieval surface + shipped spec packet with accepted ADRs + stable fixture?
    56	  YES -> Create a benchmark folder
    57	  NO  -> Keep results in the spec packet's evidence/ directory
    58	```
    59	
    60	### Trigger Signals
    61	
    62	An MCP-promotion folder is warranted when:
    63	
    64	- An ADR just promoted a non-trivial default change (a new embedder, reranker, retrieval pipeline, or runtime setting), and operators inside the MCP code will ask "why this default?"
    65	- A reader has already asked "where are the benchmark numbers?" and you pointed at a deep spec path — that question recurs every time someone touches the MCP code.
    66	- You are about to write the same comparison table twice (a README and a release note), or a sibling skill's benchmark folder has an analogous retrieval surface.
    67	
    68	### When NOT to Use
    69	
    70	Use another `sk-doc` packet when:
    71	
    72	- The benchmark is still in progress or lacks an accepted decision record.
    73	- The result is a single unreplayable data point with no stable fixture or replay commands.
    74	- The target skill has no MCP server or no measurable retrieval, quality, runtime, or throughput surface.
    75	- The user only needs a release note or changelog row. Use `create-changelog`.
    76	- The user wants to audit, validate, score, or optimize existing benchmark markdown without authoring a benchmark-family artifact. Use `create-quality-control`.
    77	- The task is a general benchmark design exercise rather than promotion of an already-curated run.
    78	- A re-run confirms the same headline; update the existing `benchmark-report.md` with a re-run note instead.
    79	- The result mixes data from different MCP stacks and asks for a single comparative verdict.
    80	- The task is to hand-edit a `skill-benchmark-report.md` (renderer-owned) or to define how any benchmark is *scored* — a rubric, evaluator, reviewer verdict, or D1-D5 weight. Those stay lane-local in deep-improvement; this packet authors inputs, indexes, and reports, not scoring (sections 10-11).
    81	- The benchmark is a one-off or experimental artifact that fits none of the six families — for example a standalone capability probe such as `sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/vision-audit-benchmark.md`. These stay lane-local as their own document; this packet's taxonomy does not absorb them, and there is no "misc" family.
    82	
    83	If unsure, default to "not yet." Promotion is cheap after rigor; reverting a premature folder costs more.
    84	
    85	---
    86	
    87	## 2. SMART ROUTING
    88	
    89	### Benchmark Families
    90	
    91	Route to the right family before authoring. The **OWNS** column is what this packet authors; **Routes to** names a lane-owned artifact (renderer, scoring contract, runner) for disambiguation only.
    92	
    93	| Family | What it measures | Lives at | create-benchmark OWNS (here) | Routes to (lane-owned) | Section |
    94	| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
    95	| MCP promotion (`shared`) | Retrieval / quality / runtime / throughput from a shipped MCP stack | `<skill>/mcp-server/benchmarks/benchmark-<YYYY-MM-DD>/` | `benchmark-report.md` + `source.md` templates and the report contract | Owned here | §3-8 |
    96	| Behavior (`behavior_benchmark`) | Executor-model behavior at a deep-loop mode's invocation surface | `<mode>/behavior-benchmark/` | Index, scenario, and baseline templates + the authoring guide | Measurement contract → `system-deep-loop/shared/behavior-benchmark/framework.md` | §9 |
    97	| Conformance (`conformance_benchmark`) | Deterministic artifact conformance against a named authority through a peer adapter | `<mode>/assets/conformance-benchmark/<benchmark-id>/` | README/index + contract + lane-config + fixture-manifest templates + guide | Adapter implementation, S-dimension/severity semantics, convergence, reducer/report → deep-alignment | §12 |
    98	| Skill-benchmark (`skill_benchmark`, Lane C) | Whether a skill is well-routed, discoverable, efficient, and useful | `<skill>/benchmark/<run-label>/` | The storage guide + the hub `benchmark/README.md` index template | `skill-benchmark-report.md` render → `build-report.cjs`; D1-D5 scoring → deep-improvement `scoring-contract.md` | §10 |
    99	| Model-benchmark (`model_benchmark`, Lane B) | What a model or prompt framework produces against a held-out oracle | `system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/` | Code-task, pattern/capability, and reviewer fixture templates + the profile template + the fixture guide | Evaluator / scorer / reviewer-verdict contract → deep-improvement lane | §11 |
   100	| Agent-improvement (`agent_improvement`, Lane A) | An agent's quality across five dimensions | deep-improvement lane (in-lane) | Authoring guide ([guide](references/agent-improvement/agent-improvement-authoring-guide.md)) | Code-owned rubric/config; run by `/deep:agent-improvement` | §14 |
   101	
   102	### Routing Decision
   103	
   104	Route by the table above; two hard stops: never hand-write a `skill-benchmark-report.md` — it is renderer-owned; never change how any benchmark is *scored* — the scoring contracts are lane-local.
   105	
   106	### Smart Router Pseudocode
   107	
   108	Benchmark families ARE the runtime routing key. `discover_markdown_resources()` and
   109	`_guard_in_skill()` are the shared canonical helpers
   110	([skill-smart-router.md](../create-skill/assets/skill/skill-smart-router.md)); only the
   111	family key and tiered fallback vary:
   112	
   113	```python
   114	DEFAULT_RESOURCE = "references/shared/README.md"
   115	FAMILIES = ["behavior_benchmark", "conformance_benchmark", "skill_benchmark", "model_benchmark",
   116	            "agent_improvement", "mcp_promotion"]
   117	# Resource dirs are kebab-case filesystem names while the snake_case family keys above stay
   118	# machine identifiers, so disk_key kebab-cases the key. mcp_promotion is the one family whose
   119	# templates live under the shared/ key rather than a same-named dir.
   120	FAMILY_DISK_KEY = {"mcp_promotion": "shared"}
   121	UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [
   122	    "Confirm the benchmark family (MCP promotion, behavior, conformance, skill, model, agent)",
   123	    "Confirm what is authored here vs lane-owned, then the storage location and run label",
   124	    "For a command benchmark, author BOTH a behavior and a conformance package for the "
   125	    "command surface and compose them via the matrix manifest "
   126	    "(references/shared/command-benchmark-composition.md)",
   127	]
   128	
   129	COMMAND_BENCHMARK_GUIDES = ["references/behavior-benchmark/behavior-benchmark-guide.md",
   130	                            "references/conformance-benchmark/conformance-benchmark-authoring-guide.md",
   131	                            "references/shared/command-benchmark-composition.md"]
   132	
   133	def route_benchmark_request(request):
   134	    inventory = discover_markdown_resources()
   135	    loaded, seen = [], set()
   136	    routing_key = get_routing_key(request, FAMILIES)
   137	
   138	    # A command benchmark is a composition, not a family key, but it IS routable by
   139	    # name: detected, it loads BOTH family guides plus the composition standard so
   140	    # the author can build the behavior and conformance packages and bind them via
   141	    # the matrix manifest. It stays out of FAMILIES because no single guide answers
   142	    # it — the composite branch is what makes "route by name" honest.
   143	    if is_command_benchmark_request(request):                    # Tier 0 (composite)
   144	        for path in COMMAND_BENCHMARK_GUIDES:
   145	            load_if_available(path, inventory, loaded, seen)
   146	        return {"load_level": "COMMAND_BENCHMARK_COMPOSITE", "resources": loaded}
   147	
   148	    if routing_key == "unknown":                                 # Tier 1
   149	        load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE, inventory, loaded, seen)
   150	        return {"load_level": "UNKNOWN_FALLBACK",
   151	                "disambiguation_checklist": UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST, "resources": loaded}
   152	
   153	    disk_key = FAMILY_DISK_KEY.get(routing_key, routing_key.replace("_", "-"))
   154	    keyed = sorted(p for p in inventory if p.startswith(
   155	        (f"references/{disk_key}/", f"assets/{disk_key}/", "references/shared/")))
   156	    if not keyed:                                                # Tier 2
   157	        load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE, inventory, loaded, seen)
   158	        return {"routing_key": routing_key,
   159	                "notice": f"'{routing_key}' guide only; fixtures/scoring stay lane-owned", "resources": loaded}
   160	
   161	    for path in keyed:                                           # Tier 3
   162	        load_if_available(path, inventory, loaded, seen)
   163	    return {"routing_key": routing_key, "resources": loaded}
   164	```
   165	
   166	### Command Benchmark (composition, not a family)
   167	
   168	A "command benchmark" is not a seventh family key. It **composes** the behavior
   169	and conformance families over the OpenCode command surface — one `behavior-benchmark`
   170	package plus one `conformance-benchmark` package — bound by a lane-owned matrix
   171	manifest and driven by a launcher that reports both axes without averaging. The
   172	composition standard and the matrix-manifest field shape live in
   173	[`references/shared/command-benchmark-composition.md`](references/shared/command-benchmark-composition.md).
   174	It is not a family key — no single family guide answers it — but it is routable by
   175	name: the Tier-0 composite branch above loads BOTH the behavior and conformance
   176	authoring guides plus that composition doc, so an author who asks for a "command
   177	benchmark" gets the two axes and the binding standard together. Only a request too
   178	vague to detect as a command benchmark falls through to the unknown-fallback
   179	checklist, whose command-benchmark line points to the same three resources.
   180	
   181	### Family Boundary
   182	
   183	This nested `sk-doc` packet owns benchmark *authoring* only — no measurement contract (rubrics, renderers, scorers, evaluator/verdict contracts stay lane-local; Lane A gets a guide template only, `assets: N/A`). The single advisor identity lives at the `sk-doc` hub root; never add a packet-local `graph-metadata.json`.
   184	
   185	---
   186	
   187	## 3. REQUIRED PACKAGE SHAPE
   188	
   189	Author or update this package shape inside the consuming skill:
   190	
   191	```text
   192	mcp-server/benchmarks/
   193	├── README.md
   194	└── benchmark-<YYYY-MM-DD>/
   195	    ├── benchmark-report.md
   196	    ├── results.csv
   197	    ├── per-probe.jsonl
   198	    ├── runtime-measurements.md
   199	    └── source.md
