    13	
    14	# opencode Surface — System-Code Evidence
    15	
    16	**Domain evidence** and shared workflow doctrine for OpenCode system code (the `.opencode/` tree: skills, agents, commands, plugins, MCP servers, config, changelogs, and runtime bridge wiring). This surface owns the implement -> debug -> verify phases through the workflow references below, then slices evidence by the detected language so a TypeScript task never pulls the Python/shell/config guides.
    17	
    18	Detection is two-step. First, the surface trigger is work under `.opencode/` (including `SKILL.md`, descriptors, commands, agents, plugins, MCP servers, assets, scripts, and changelogs). Second, once the OpenCode surface is selected, file extensions and local markers select the language trio: `.cjs`/`.mjs`/`.js` -> JavaScript, `.ts`/`.tsx`/`.mts`/`.d.ts` -> TypeScript, `.py` plus `argparse` -> Python, `.sh`/`.bash` -> shell, `.rs` -> Rust, `.json`/`.jsonc`/`.yaml`/`.yml` plus `graph-metadata` or `spec-folder` -> config. For Rust, when no `.rs` file is present, local `Cargo.toml`/`Cargo.lock` markers select it after the OpenCode surface is established; napi-rs and wasm-bindgen vocabulary are additional intent signals, not cross-project surface detectors.
    19	
    20	## 1. WHEN THE HUB BUNDLES THIS
    21	
    22	- The task touches `.opencode/` system code — a skill, agent, command, plugin, MCP server, or descriptor/config.
    23	- The active workflow phase needs a language standard, a language-agnostic organization pattern, a hook contract, an alignment-verification procedure, or an authoring checklist.
    24	- This surface owns edits, tests, and verification through the workflow references; hand off formal findings-first review to `code-review` and author-side quality gates to `code-quality`.
    25	
    26	## 2. REFERENCE MAP
    27	
    28	Language standards — after `.opencode/` selects this surface, load ONLY the detected language's trio (`style-guide.md`, `quality-standards.md`, `quick-reference.md`):
    29	- TypeScript — `references/typescript/`
    30	- Python — `references/python/`
    31	- Shell — `references/shell/`
    32	- Rust (napi-rs/WASM/sidecar interop under TypeScript parity) — `references/rust/`
    33	- Config (JSON/JSONC/YAML descriptors and route assets) — `references/config/`
    34	- JavaScript (CommonJS/ESM plugins) — `references/javascript/`
    35	
    36	Language-agnostic shared tier (`references/shared/`, always kept within OpenCode regardless of language):
    37	- `universal_patterns.md`, `code_organization.md`
    38	- `hooks.md` — runtime hook entrypoints, checked-in Claude wiring, OpenCode plugin-bridge delivery, and wrapper reachability; defer to that file for current hook infrastructure instead of duplicating it here
    39	- `alignment-verification-automation.md` — the alignment-drift verifier
    40	
    41	Workflow (`references/`): `workflow-implement.md`, `workflow-debug.md`, `workflow-verify.md` — this surface owns the implement -> debug -> verify phases; these are the shared phase doctrine.
    42	
    43	## 2b. SMART ROUTING (machine-readable)
    44	
    45	This block is the deterministic projection of code-opencode's own reference/asset routing, consumed by the skill-benchmark router-replay; keep it in sync with the parent hub union.
    46	
    47	```python
    48	# code-opencode owns its intent -> reference/asset routing. Paths are relative to
    49	# this skill root. The parent sk-code hub RESOURCE_MAP is the union of this map
    50	# (re-prefixed with code-opencode/) and the sibling code-webflow map plus the
    51	# parent-owned universal/shared tier; a drift guard enforces that equality.
    52	DEFAULT_RESOURCE = [
    53	    "references/shared/universal-patterns/naming-and-commenting.md",
    54	    "references/shared/universal-patterns/organization-security-and-examples.md",
    55	    "references/shared/code-organization/overview-and-module-organization.md",
    56	    "references/shared/code-organization/imports-and-exports.md",
    57	    "references/shared/code-organization/directory-and-test-conventions.md",
    58	]
    59	
    60	INTENT_SIGNALS = {
    61	    "IMPLEMENTATION":     {"weight": 1, "keywords": ["implement", "build", "create", "feature", "component", "module", "authoring"]},
    62	    "CODE_QUALITY":       {"weight": 1, "keywords": ["lint", "format", "quality gate", "naming", "standards", "code smell"]},
    63	    "VERIFICATION":       {"weight": 1, "keywords": ["verify", "passing", "type-check", "alignment drift", "completion claim"]},
