.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:19:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:20:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:21:## 1. OVERVIEW
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:22:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:23:### Purpose
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:24:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:25:Provide a systematic pass for non-security defects that still cause outages, regressions, or high maintenance cost.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:26:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:27:### Usage
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:28:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:29:Run this pass on every findings-first review; walk each section against the changed diff and cite file:line for anything flagged.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:30:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:31:### Core Principle
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:32:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:33:Prioritize silent-failure and data-corruption risks above stylistic concerns.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:34:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:35:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:36:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:37:## 2. ERROR HANDLING
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:38:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:39:Flag:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:40:- Swallowed exceptions (`catch {}` or log-only catches).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:41:- Overly broad exception handling hiding root causes.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:42:- Missing async error propagation.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:43:- User-facing leakage of internal stack traces.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:44:- Missing fallback behavior for recoverable failures.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:45:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:46:Review prompts:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:47:- "Will callers know this failed?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:48:- "Is there enough context to debug without exposing internals?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:49:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:50:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:51:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:52:## 3. PERFORMANCE AND SCALING
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:53:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:54:Flag:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:55:- N+1 query patterns.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:56:- Per-item network/database calls that should be batched.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:57:- Expensive work in hot loops without memoization/cache.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:58:- Synchronous blocking work in request paths.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:59:- Unbounded collections and memory growth risks.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:60:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:61:Review prompts:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:62:- "How does this behave with 10x data volume?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:63:- "Can this call path be batched or cached safely?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:64:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:65:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:66:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:67:## 4. BOUNDARY CONDITIONS
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:68:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:69:Check:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:70:- Null/undefined handling and optional chaining misuse.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:71:- Empty collection behavior for first/last/indexed access.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:72:- Numeric boundaries (division by zero, overflow, negative values).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:73:- String boundaries (empty, whitespace-only, very long input, unicode).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:74:- Off-by-one errors in loops, pagination, and slicing.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:75:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:76:Common risky patterns:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:77:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:78:```javascript
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:79:const first = items[0]              // no empty check
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:80:const avg = total / count           // count may be zero
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:81:if (value) { /* skips valid 0 */ }  // truthy trap
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:82:```
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:83:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:84:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:85:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:86:## 5. DATA FLOW AND CONTRACT SAFETY
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:87:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:88:Flag:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:89:- Function or method signature changes that break existing callers (added required parameters, removed parameters, changed return types).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:90:- New null or undefined return paths introduced where callers expect a value.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:91:- Data transformation functions that silently drop fields, truncate values, or lose type precision.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:92:- Default parameter value changes that alter behavior for existing callers without updating call sites.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:93:- Implicit behavioral contract changes (sort order, iteration order, timing guarantees) not documented in the diff.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:94:- Public API response shape changes without versioning or migration path.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:95:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:96:Review prompts:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:97:- "If an existing caller is not updated, will it still work correctly after this change?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:98:- "Does any data transformation lose information that downstream consumers need?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:99:- "Are implicit behavioral guarantees (ordering, timing, idempotency) preserved?"
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:100:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:101:Severity guidance:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:102:- P0 for breaking changes to public APIs or shared interfaces with no migration path.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:103:- P1 for new null returns or type changes that existing callers do not handle.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:104:- P2 for implicit contract changes with low blast radius.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:105:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:106:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:107:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:108:## 6. MAINTAINABILITY SIGNALS
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:109:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:110:Watch for:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:111:- Repeated logic with inconsistent behavior.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:112:- Magic literals where domain constants are expected.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:113:- Overly nested control flow reducing readability.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:114:- Hidden coupling through global/shared mutable state.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:115:- Tests missing for newly introduced edge cases.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:116:- Functions exceeding 20 lines or 4+ nesting levels without structural justification.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:117:- Deep method chaining across more than two object boundaries (Law of Demeter: a.b().c().d()).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:118:- Functions that produce side effects not implied by their name or signature (Principle of Least Astonishment).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:119:- Error messages that lack actionable context for debugging (missing what failed and what to try).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:120:- TODO, FIXME, or HACK comments in production code paths without an associated tracking reference (issue link or ticket number).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:121:- Hardcoded environment-specific values (URLs, ports, timeout thresholds) that should be externalized for deployment flexibility.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:122:- Hand-rolled standard-library behavior where the language or runtime already provides a clear, readable primitive — prefer the standard API when behavior and edge cases match.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:123:- Custom code or a dependency duplicating a native platform/runtime capability without a current requirement the native feature cannot satisfy.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:124:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:125:Decision cue: if reviewers cannot explain intent quickly, maintenance risk is likely at least P2.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:126:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:127:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:128:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:129:## 7. KISS / DRY ENFORCEMENT
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:130:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:131:### KISS Checks
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:132:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:133:Flag:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:134:- New abstraction layers without a current behavior need.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:135:- Generic helpers used in only one place.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:136:- Workflow complexity introduced "for future flexibility" without evidence.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:137:- Features, parameters, or configuration options added for speculative future use without a current requirement (YAGNI).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:138:- New code not traceable to a current requirement (a feature, parameter, branch, or config that nothing in the stated scope asked for) — recommend removal (see removal-plan.md), not just simplification. Ask: was this asked for? If the requirement were dropped, would anything break? If not, it is a removal candidate. P2 by default per the severity rule below; escalate to P1 only when the unneeded code adds attack surface, contract obligations, or regression/maintenance risk.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:139:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:140:### DRY Checks
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:141:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:142:Flag:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:143:- Duplicated constants/rules across modules.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:144:- Copy-paste branches with minor name changes.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:145:- Repeated validation/parsing blocks that can share one source.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:146:- Abstractions extracted from only two instances without evidence of a shared concept. Apply the Rule of Three before consolidating to avoid premature generalization (AHA).
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:147:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:148:Severity guidance:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:149:- P2 default for stylistic duplication/complexity.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:150:- Escalate to P1 if duplication or complexity introduces behavior/regression risk.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:151:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:152:Intentional-simplification evidence:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:153:- A concrete `ceiling:` comment (naming the shortcut, its ceiling, and the upgrade path) is evidence that a "too simple" or "missing feature" KISS/YAGNI finding is deliberate — downgrade or suppress that P2 finding. This NEVER applies to security, auth, persistence, sandboxing, public-contract, or correctness findings; those are judged on their own contract regardless of any comment.
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:154:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:155:---
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:156:
.opencode/skills/sk-code/code-review/assets/code-quality-checklist.md:157:## 8. RELATED RESOURCES
