.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:2:title: "Feature Specification: Compiled Routing — Default-On Decision & Safe-Cutover Contract"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:3:description: "Settle whether SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING should become the repo's effective default and, if so, on what safe path. The compiled router is built, wired, and inert behind a default-off flag: the P4b flip already moved all seven hubs' manifests to servingAuthority: compiled, and the live advisor consumes them only when the flag is 1, only for hubs in a hardcoded allowlist, and even then attaches the compiled decision as ADDITIVE metadata that never changes which skill is recommended. This phase records the decision — default-on is a Phase-4 OUTCOME, not a switch-flip — and specifies the four contracts that make an eventual global default-on safe and reversible: (P0) document the flag in ENV-REFERENCE and make the verify harness distinguish drift-to-legacy from breakage plus a per-hub serving-status readout; (P1) a drift-detection CI that recomputes each hub's live hash against its minted manifest and fails 're-mint required'; (P2) a canary default-on in one env profile with the repo default staying off; (P3) a data-driven eligibility rule (compiled-eligible IFF a valid fresh manifest exists) that single-sources the duplicated allowlist and makes no-manifest skills legacy by construction; (P4) a staged, hub-by-hub global default-on that flips the two code predicates and the seven SKILL.md directives in lockstep while keeping =0 as the documented kill-switch. The frozen benchmark scorer is never touched and every step is byte-exact reversible."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:5:  - "compiled routing default-on decision"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:6:  - "SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING flip default"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:12:    packet_pointer: "sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:16:    next_safe_action: "Begin P0 on operator go-ahead"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:28:      - "Flip the default now or adopt the phased path? Adopt the phased path, settled on the analysis; operator may override."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:37:- Scope drift, vague acceptance criteria, and optimistic done-language without evidence.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:40:# Compiled Routing — Default-On Decision & Safe-Cutover Contract
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:44:The compiled skill-router is built, hardened, wired into the live advisor, and **inert behind a default-off flag**. The sibling P4b work (`011-runtime-engine`) already flipped all seven hubs' activation manifests to `servingAuthority: compiled`; what remains gated is whether the runtime *consumes* that state, and that gate is `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING`. The parent goal asks to make compiled routing "the effective default."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:46:This phase is a **decision packet**, not a flip. It records — against verified source evidence, not narrative — that flipping the repo default to ON **today changes zero routing decisions** and therefore trades real operational surface for no behavioral gain, and it specifies the four contracts (P0→P4) under which a global default-on becomes a safe, observable, reversible *outcome*. The single load-bearing finding: in the only live integration point, the compiled decision is attached as **additive metadata** to a recommendation the legacy path has already computed — so enabling the flag can only make an extra `compiledRoute` field appear or silently not-appear; it cannot change which skill is recommended (`advisor-recommend.ts:357-374`, decisive line `:371`).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:48:The ruling is **settled: adopt the phased path** — decided on the analysis and source verification above (per the session directive to settle the decision), reversible, and open to operator override to flip-now. No runtime change follows from this decision; a separate operator go-ahead gates the start of P0 implementation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:58:| **Priority** | P0 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:59:| **Status** | Ruling settled — adopt the phased path (P0→P4), decided on the analysis; reversible and operator-overridable. No runtime implementation started; a separate operator go-ahead gates P0. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:62:| **Migration stage** | Decision gate preceding P0 (documentation + observability); default-on is the P4 outcome |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:63:| **Blast radius** | Decision + contracts only (no code change here). The contracts it governs range from zero-blast (docs) to the highest-blast change in the program (global serving default), each staged and reversible |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:73:The parent goal frames "compiled routing as the effective default" as a switch to flip. Verified source evidence shows that framing is unsafe for five independent, non-overlapping reasons:
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:76:2. **Silent drift is the steady state.** The serve-time shim recomputes the decision from live hub config; on any mismatch, missing resolver, or error it emits a `{ servingAuthority: "legacy" }` sentinel (`compiled-route.cjs:36-39`), which the advisor maps to `undefined` (`advisor-recommend.ts:351`). Any edit to a hub's `SKILL.md`/router config reverts that hub to legacy invisibly until its manifest is re-minted. This repo churns hub config constantly, so "compiled" would spend much of its life silently on legacy.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:77:3. **No observability.** Nothing distinguishes "serving compiled" from "silently fell back to legacy." A drifted hub and a broken hub read identically.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:78:4. **Undocumented flag = governance violation.** `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` is absent from `ENV-REFERENCE.md`, which the project constitution (CLAUDE.md §6) mandates as the source of truth for flag defaults. Flipping an undocumented flag violates that mandate.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:79:5. **Kill-switch inversion.** Today, absence-of-var = legacy = safe. After a naive default-flip, absence = compiled, silently changing every runtime/hook/CI/launcher that assumed "absent = legacy."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:81:A sixth, structural fragility (found this phase, under-weighted in prior handovers): the runtime front door `bin/compiled-route.cjs` resolves its resolver from a path **inside the spec tree** (`compiled-route.cjs:16-21` → `007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs`). A spec renumber/re-nest silently breaks every compiled route to the legacy sentinel — the repo's own reorganization is a drift engine.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:85:Record the decision that default-on is a Phase-4 *outcome*, not a switch, and specify the four contracts (P0→P4) that make an eventual global default-on safe, observable, and byte-exact reversible — so that when the flag is flipped, compiled routing does something legacy cannot, drift is caught by CI rather than discovered in production, and the kill-switch (`=0`) is a documented, load-bearing control rather than an accident of variable absence.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:96:- The **ruling** (settled): default-on is a staged P4 outcome; the phased path P0→P4 is adopted as the program of record, decided on the analysis and reversible. A separate operator go-ahead gates the start of P0 implementation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:98:- The **drift-detection CI contract**: recompute each hub's live config hash vs its minted manifest; fail "re-mint required" on mismatch; wire "edit a hub → re-mint" as an enforced rule, not a remembered one.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:99:- The **observability contract**: the verify harness must classify drift-to-legacy as *degraded/expected*, not *broken*, and expose a per-hub serving-status readout (compiled-serving | legacy-fallback | drifted).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:100:- The **migration map** P0→P4 with reversibility and the frozen-scorer pin at every step, including promoting or explicitly documenting the runtime→spec-tree resolver coupling as a named drift source.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:105:- Editing the frozen benchmark scorer (`router-replay.cjs`, `score-skill-benchmark.cjs`, `load-playbook-scenarios.cjs`) — [why] pinned and non-negotiable across the whole program.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:106:- Actually flipping `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` to a repo default in this phase — [why] this phase decides and contracts; the flip is the P4 execution phase, gated on P0–P3 landing green.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:107:- The `sk-doc:create-skill` generator alignment and the skill-benchmark alignment — [why] delivered in the sibling phases `013-create-skill-alignment` and `014-benchmark-alignment`, which consume this phase's fallback and eligibility contracts.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:113:| `012-default-on-decision/spec.md` | Create | This decision spec |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:114:| `012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md` | Create | The ruling, the verified evidence with file:line receipts, alternatives weighed, and the fallback/drift/observability contracts in full |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:115:| `012-default-on-decision/{plan.md, tasks.md, checklist.md, implementation-summary.md}` | Create | Level-3 planning, task breakdown, verification checklist, and Planned-state completion record |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:126:### P0 - Blockers (MUST complete)
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:128:| ID | Requirement | Acceptance Criteria |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:131:| REQ-002 | Specify the fallback contract precisely and single-sourced. | The contract defines that a hub is compiled-served IFF a valid, fresh manifest exists AND `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1` AND the hub is eligible; every other state resolves to the legacy sentinel with no behavior change. The eligibility predicate is named as the single source both `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` must derive from (delivered in P3). |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:132:| REQ-003 | Specify the drift-detection CI contract. | The contract defines: recompute each hub's live config hash, compare to its minted manifest digest, exit non-zero with "re-mint required: <hub>" on mismatch; and the enforced rule "editing a hub's routing inputs requires re-minting its manifest in the same change." |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:133:| REQ-004 | Specify the observability contract. | The contract defines a per-hub serving-status readout with three states (compiled-serving | legacy-fallback | drifted) and requires the verify harness to score drift-to-legacy as degraded/expected rather than a hard failure, so a red signal means breakage, not routine churn. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:134:| REQ-005 | Record the P0→P4 migration map with reversibility and the frozen-scorer pin at every step, and name the runtime→spec-tree resolver coupling as a P0 remediation (promote the resolver to a stable runtime path OR document the coupling as an explicit drift source). | `decision-record.md` and `plan.md` carry the ordered P0→P4 map; each step names its rollback; the scorer pin and "no routing-decision change" invariant are restated per step. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:136:### P1 - Required (complete OR user-approved deferral)
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:138:| ID | Requirement | Acceptance Criteria |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:141:| REQ-007 | Cross-link the two dependent alignment phases so the fallback and eligibility contracts have exactly one home. | `013-create-skill-alignment` and `014-benchmark-alignment` reference this phase's contracts rather than restating them; this spec's RELATED DOCUMENTS lists both. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:150:- **SC-001**: The decision is legible — a reader can reconstruct, from receipts, why flipping the default today is zero-benefit and why the phased path is recommended, without re-deriving it from source.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:151:- **SC-002**: The fallback contract is unambiguous and single-sourced: "no valid fresh manifest ⇒ legacy" holds by construction, and the eligibility predicate has one named home for P3 to implement.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:152:- **SC-003**: The drift-CI and observability contracts are specified concretely enough to implement in P0/P1 without further design.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:153:- **SC-004**: The P0→P4 map is reversible at every step, restates the frozen-scorer pin and the no-routing-change invariant per step, and names the resolver spec-path coupling as a P0 remediation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:154:- **SC-005**: The ruling's status honestly reflects reality — settled on the analysis (adopt the phased path), reversible and operator-overridable — with no premature "default-on" or "implementation started" claim.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:165:| Risk | Premise capture — treating default-on as a switch | Flips an undocumented flag that inverts the kill-switch for zero routing benefit | This decision reframes default-on as a P4 outcome gated on P0–P3; the flip is never this phase's action |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:166:| Risk | Silent drift normalized as "compiled" | A drifted hub serves legacy while dashboards claim compiled | P1 drift-CI fails re-mint-required; P0 observability distinguishes drifted from broken |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:167:| Risk | Duplicated allowlist diverges | `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` drift apart, mis-gating hubs | P3 single-sources eligibility to "valid fresh manifest exists"; both predicates derive from it |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:168:| Risk | Runtime resolver coupled to a spec-tree path | A spec renumber breaks all compiled routing to the sentinel | REQ-005 P0 remediation: promote the resolver to a stable runtime path or document the coupling as a named drift source with a guard |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:169:| Dependency | Frozen benchmark scorer (three pinned files) | Any edit invalidates the parity baseline the whole program rests on | Restated as a hard pin per migration step; never edited |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:170:| Dependency | Sibling `013`/`014` alignment phases | Onboarding (create-skill) and validation (benchmarks) must consume this phase's contracts | REQ-007 cross-links; the contracts live here once and are referenced, not restated |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:180:- **NFR-R01**: Every step P0→P4 names an explicit rollback; the P4 global default-on keeps `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` as the documented, load-bearing kill-switch.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:181:- **NFR-R02**: Because compiled routing is byte-identical to legacy for matched hubs, any step's rollback is behavior-neutral by construction, not merely by test.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:184:- **NFR-D01**: The fallback is deterministic: identical (hub config, manifest, flag) inputs always yield the same served-authority; drift is a pure function of a hash mismatch, not timing.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:187:- **NFR-A01**: Serving authority is conferred only by a valid, fresh manifest under an enabled flag for an eligible hub; nothing else grants it, and the eligibility predicate has exactly one source of truth (P3).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:195:- Hub with a stale manifest (config edited, not re-minted): live hash ≠ minted digest ⇒ legacy sentinel; P1 CI fails re-mint-required.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:198:- Drifted hub vs broken resolver: both currently read identically; P0 observability must separate "degraded/expected (drift)" from "broken (error)".
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:201:### Kill-switch
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:202:- `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` after P4 default-on: must fully restore legacy serving fleet-wide, documented as the kill-switch, not an incidental default.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:211:| Risk | 18/25 | The decision governs the highest-blast change in the program (the global serving default); the phase itself is zero-blast documentation, but its ruling is load-bearing for every later phase |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:212:| Research | 12/20 | Mechanism verified from source this phase (additive metadata, sentinel fallback, allowlist duplication, resolver coupling); residual is P0 implementation, not investigation |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:221:| Operator overrides to flip default-on now | Medium | Medium | Fallback is genuinely fail-safe today, so an early flip is survivable; still land P0 docs + observability first to satisfy governance and avoid a two-meaning red signal | Operator |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:222:| A hub edit silently reverts that hub to legacy | High | Medium | P1 drift-CI fails re-mint-required at edit time; P0 readout shows the drifted state | P1 owner |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:223:| The two hardcoded allowlists diverge | Medium | High | P3 single-sources eligibility to "valid fresh manifest exists"; both predicates derive from it | P3 owner |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:224:| A spec renumber severs the runtime resolver path | Medium | High | ADR-003: promote the resolver to a stable runtime path (recommended) or guard the path loudly | P0 owner |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:225:| Frozen scorer edited, invalidating the parity baseline | Low | High | Hard pin restated per migration step; never edited; re-hash gate aborts on drift | Whole program |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:231:- **US-001 (operator).** As the operator overseeing the cutover, I want the default-on question recorded with verifiable receipts and the settled ruling, so I can see how it was decided and override to flip-now if I choose, with full information rather than a narrative.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:234:- **US-004 (release owner).** As the owner of the eventual global flip, I want a per-hub serving-status readout and a documented `=0` kill-switch, so I can flip hub-by-hub, watch each land, and revert instantly if any hub misbehaves.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:240:- **Q1 (resolved).** The ruling is settled: adopt the phased path (default-on as a staged P4 outcome after P0–P3), decided on the analysis and reversible. An operator override to flip `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` on now remains available but is not blocking; the steelman for flipping now is recorded in `decision-record.md` ("flip it when compiled does something legacy can't").
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:241:- **Q2.** For the P0 resolver-coupling remediation: promote `resolve.cjs` out of the spec tree into a stable runtime location, or keep it in place behind a path-integrity guard that fails loudly on a renumber? (Recommendation: promote; it removes the drift source rather than guarding it.)
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:242:- **Q3.** Which single env profile hosts the P2 canary default-on (repo default staying off), and what parity + clean-fallback thresholds gate promotion from P2 to P3?
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:251:- **Build approach (P0→P4)**: See `plan.md`
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:257:- **Onboarding alignment (consumes fallback/eligibility contracts)**: `../013-create-skill-alignment/`
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/spec.md:258:- **Validation alignment (consumes fallback/eligibility contracts)**: `../014-benchmark-alignment/`
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:2:title: "Feature Specification: create-skill Compiled-Routing Alignment"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:5:  - "create-skill compiled routing alignment"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:18:- Scope drift, vague acceptance criteria, and optimistic done-language without evidence.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:21:# create-skill Compiled-Routing Alignment
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:25:`sk-doc:create-skill` can generate a parent hub, its registry/router metadata, and its first workflow packet, but it currently emits no compiled-routing directive, no activation-manifest step, and no compiled-readiness verification. A repository search beneath `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/` returns zero compiled-routing tokens. The generated hub therefore reflects the pre-v4 routing model even though the seven established hubs now carry the additive, flag-gated directive.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:27:This phase plans the onboarding-side implementation of the eligibility decision owned by `../012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md`. A generated parent hub must be born in one of two explicit states: **compiled-ready**, where create-skill mints and verifies the canonical fresh manifest, or **legacy**, where no manifest is emitted and the hub follows the existing routing path by construction. This packet references the authoritative fallback and eligibility contract; it does not redefine it.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:37:| **Priority** | P0 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:41:| **Consumed decision** | `../012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md` (eligibility and fallback authority) |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:54:The copy-from parent template, `assets/parent-skill/parent-skill-hub-template.md`, likewise contains no compiled directive. The broader create-skill workflow documents parent-hub metadata and validation, but never asks whether the new hub should mint compiled eligibility. Existing tests in `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/tests/test_create_skill_contract.py` verify the emitted paths and naming, not compiled state.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:62:Align create-skill with the v4 router model by adding the exact directive block, an explicit compiled-readiness selection, a canonical manifest-mint step, and contract tests that prove both generated states. The current implementation files remain unchanged in this documentation phase.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:73:- A new `--compiled-routing legacy|ready` option. Existing CLI calls default to `legacy` for backward compatibility; the higher-level create-skill workflow must ask authors to choose explicitly.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:75:- A post-scaffold manifest step for `ready`: call the canonical minter supplied by the P3 eligibility implementation, then verify the returned manifest is valid and fresh before reporting compiled-ready.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:77:- Create-skill workflow, README/reference, validator, and contract-test updates needed to keep the generated output and documentation synchronized.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:83:- Implementing the P3 runtime discovery and canonical manifest store; create-skill consumes those interfaces after they exist.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:84:- Changing the compiled router's decisions, the advisor recommendation, environment defaults, existing hub manifests, or existing hub directives.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:85:- Editing `router-replay.cjs`, `score-skill-benchmark.cjs`, or `load-playbook-scenarios.cjs`.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:93:> **Compiled routing (opt-in, flag-gated, additive).** When `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1`, resolve the mode via the compiled router contract first:
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:97:> Follow the returned decision — `route` (use its `targets`), `clarify`/`defer` (disambiguate), `reject` (refuse). On a `{"servingAuthority":"legacy"}` sentinel or any error, use the routing below. The front door self-gates on serving authority, and the flag is **off by default**, so this is inert until compiled routing is activated for `{{HUB_NAME}}`.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:112:| `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-skill/scripts/validate_skill_package.py` | Modify if required by the chosen P3 API | Report directive/manifest consistency and freshness through the shared predicate |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:113:| `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/scripts/tests/test_create_skill_contract.py` | Modify | Add legacy, compiled-ready, directive-rendering, and mint-failure regression cases |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:123:### P0 - Blockers (MUST complete)
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:125:| ID | Requirement | Acceptance Criteria |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:127:| REQ-001 | Consume the eligibility and fallback decision without redefining it. | create-skill calls the shared P3 minter/freshness interface and links to the decision packet; no local allowlist, freshness algorithm, or alternate fallback rule is introduced. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:129:| REQ-003 | Expose two deliberate generated states. | `--compiled-routing legacy|ready` is parent-only; existing CLI calls default to `legacy`; the higher-level workflow asks for a choice; output states either `legacy (no manifest)` or `compiled-ready (fresh manifest verified)`. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:134:### P1 - Required (complete OR user-approved deferral)
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:136:| ID | Requirement | Acceptance Criteria |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:138:| REQ-007 | Add contract tests and package validation for both states. | Tests cover directive substitution, legacy no-manifest output, ready fresh-manifest output through a test minter, stale/malformed rejection, unknown option rejection, and unchanged standalone behavior. |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:162:| Dependency | P3 canonical minter, manifest store, and freshness predicate | `ready` cannot be truthful without them | Gate implementation on the stable P3 interface; never emulate it inside create-skill |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:163:| Dependency | Data-driven runtime hub discovery | A fresh manifest alone cannot route a hub if the runtime still uses a fixed hub map | Require P3 runtime discovery before advertising ready mode |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:164:| Risk | Active scaffold and copy-from template drift | CLI-generated and manually-authored hubs receive different directives | One contract test reads both templates and compares the normalized block |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:165:| Risk | Backward-compatible default hides an author choice | Existing scripts need a default, but agent workflows should not silently choose | CLI defaults to legacy; create-skill workflow asks explicitly and reports the selected state |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:167:| Risk | P4 later changes directive semantics | The generated block could become stale | Treat the active scaffold and seven hub directives as one lockstep surface in P4 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:177:- **NFR-D01**: Given the same hub inputs and P3 minter version, manifest minting and readiness classification are deterministic.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:221:| Scope | 13/25 | One generator path, two templates, workflow docs, validation, and tests |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:222:| Risk | 12/25 | Backward-compatible default and fail-safe fallback bound runtime risk |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:223:| Research | 8/20 | Depends on the stable P3 minter and manifest-location interface |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:232:- What exact callable/CLI name and return schema will P3 expose for canonical manifest minting and freshness verification?
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:233:- Will the P3 canonical manifest live beside each hub, in a central runtime store, or behind an abstract resolver? create-skill must consume the interface rather than bind to the current phase-local path.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:241:- **Eligibility and fallback authority**: `../012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md`
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/013-create-skill-alignment/spec.md:242:- **Default-on program**: `../012-default-on-decision/spec.md`
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:2:title: "Decision Record: Compiled Routing Default-On"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:3:description: "Three decisions governing whether and how SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING becomes the repo's effective default: defer global default-on to a staged P4 outcome, single-source compiled eligibility to a valid fresh manifest, and remediate the runtime-to-spec-tree resolver coupling."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:5:  - "compiled routing default-on decision record"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:12:    packet_pointer: "sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:16:    next_safe_action: "Begin P0 on operator go-ahead"
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:28:      - "Flip the default now or adopt the phased path? Adopt the phased path (ADR-001), settled on the analysis; operator may override."
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:31:# Decision Record: Compiled Routing Default-On
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:40:## ADR-001: Defer global default-on to a staged P4 outcome
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:55:The parent goal asks to make compiled routing the effective default, framing it as flipping `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` from off to on. Reading the live integration point shows that framing buys nothing and costs real surface. The advisor enters compiled routing only through `enrichCompiledRoutes()` at `advisor-recommend.ts:357`. With the flag unset that function returns its input untouched (`:362`). With the flag set it maps over recommendations the legacy path already computed and attaches `compiledRoute` as an additive sibling field, `{ ...recommendation, compiledRoute }` at `:371`, and never recomputes the chosen `skillId` or `workflowMode`. Turning the flag on can only make that extra field appear or, on drift, silently not appear. It cannot change which skill is recommended.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:57:The sibling `011-runtime-engine` already flipped all seven hubs' manifests to `servingAuthority: compiled`, held inert behind the default-off flag. So the destination machinery exists. What does not exist is the reason to flip: today the flip is behavior-neutral by construction.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:62:- The three frozen benchmark scorer files (`router-replay.cjs`, `score-skill-benchmark.cjs`, `load-playbook-scenarios.cjs`) are pinned and never edited.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:63:- `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING` is absent from `ENV-REFERENCE.md`, which CLAUDE.md section 6 mandates as the source of truth for flag defaults. Flipping an undocumented flag violates that mandate.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:64:- The serve-time shim recomputes each hub's decision from live config and falls back to a `{ servingAuthority: "legacy" }` sentinel on any mismatch (`compiled-route.cjs:36-39`), which the advisor maps to `undefined` (`advisor-recommend.ts:351`). Editing a hub reverts it to legacy until re-minted, with nothing to observe the reversion.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:73:**We chose**: Treat global default-on as the final outcome of a four-step program (P0 through P4), not a one-line default change made now.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:75:**How it works**: P0 documents the flag in `ENV-REFERENCE.md` and makes the verify harness distinguish drift-to-legacy from breakage plus a per-hub serving-status readout. P1 adds a drift-detection CI that recomputes each hub's live hash against its minted manifest and fails re-mint-required. P2 canaries default-on in one env profile while the repo default stays off. P3 replaces the two hardcoded allowlists with a data-driven eligibility rule (see ADR-002). P4 flips the repo default hub-by-hub, keeping `=0` as the documented kill-switch. The flip becomes worthwhile precisely when compiled routing does something legacy cannot (a consumed decision, a caught drift), which P0 through P3 create.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:77:**Settlement**: This ruling is settled on the merits of the analysis above (the five premise-failures and the resolver coupling), as the session directive to settle the decision using the fresh-Opus analysis requires. It is a reversible documentation decision: no runtime change follows from it, and the operator may override to flip-now at any time. Acceptance settles the sequencing (phased) only; a separate operator go-ahead gates the start of P0 implementation.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:88:| **Phased P0 to P4 (chosen)** | Reversible at every step; drift caught by CI not production; flag documented before it is load-bearing; the flip lands when it carries benefit | Four phases of enabling work before the headline default flips | 9/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:89:| Flip the repo default now | One-line change; matches the literal goal wording | Zero routing benefit (additive metadata only); normalizes silent drift; inverts the kill-switch (absence becomes compiled); violates the ENV-REFERENCE governance mandate | 3/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:90:| Abandon compiled routing | Removes the drift surface entirely | Discards a built, proven, reversible system and the parity work behind it; loses the future benefit the phased path unlocks | 2/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:92:**Why this one**: The destination (compiled as the effective default) is not rejected, it is sequenced. Flipping today trades governance and observability surface for a benefit that is currently zero, so the correct move is to build the benefit and the safety net first, then flip. The steelman for flipping now is honest and recorded: if compiled cannot help and cannot hurt routing, the only net effects are the ones that can hurt, so flip it once compiled does something legacy cannot. That condition is exactly what P0 through P3 establish.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:102:- The eventual flip is observable: a per-hub readout shows compiled-serving vs legacy-fallback vs drifted, so a red signal means breakage rather than routine churn.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:103:- Drift is caught in CI at edit time, not discovered in production after a hub silently reverts to legacy.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:104:- The kill-switch stays meaningful: `=0` remains the documented control, and variable-absence keeps its safe legacy meaning until the P4 flip deliberately changes it.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:107:- Four phases of enabling work precede the headline default change. Mitigation: each phase ships standalone value (docs, CI, canary, single-sourced eligibility) rather than being pure overhead.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:113:| Operator overrides to flip now | M | The fallback is genuinely fail-safe today, so an early flip is survivable; but P0 documentation and observability should still land first to satisfy governance and avoid a two-meaning red signal |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:125:| 1 | **Necessary?** | PASS | The governance gap (undocumented flag) and the silent-drift surface are real today, independent of any future flip |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:141:- P0: `ENV-REFERENCE.md` gains the flag entry; the verify harness gains drift-vs-breakage classification and a per-hub serving-status readout.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:142:- P1: a drift-detection CI job plus the enforced rule that editing a hub's routing inputs re-mints its manifest in the same change.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:143:- P2 to P4: a canary env profile, the data-driven eligibility rule (ADR-002), then the staged hub-by-hub default flip.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:145:**How to roll back**: Nothing in this phase changes runtime behavior, so there is nothing to roll back here. Across the program, `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=0` restores legacy serving fleet-wide, and each per-hub flip retains a byte-identical prior manifest for a byte-exact per-hub revert.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:159:| **Status** | Accepted (design direction; implemented in P3) |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:168:Which hubs are compiled-eligible is hardcoded in two places: `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` in `advisor-recommend.ts:41` and `HUB_CHILD` in `compiled-route.cjs:23`. Two hand-maintained lists drift apart. A newly created skill is compiled-invisible with no defined way to opt in, and `create-skill` today has zero compiled-routing awareness (a repo grep for compiled-routing tokens under the create-skill mode returns nothing).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:220:| Migration removes the hardcoded sets prematurely | M | Keep the sets as a pinned fallback until P3 parity is proven, then delete in one change |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:234:| 4 | **Fits Goal?** | PASS | Directly enables a safe global default-on by making eligibility a maintained property, not a code constant |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:247:- P3: a single eligibility predicate keyed on manifest freshness; `COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS` and `HUB_CHILD` become derived, then removed as hand-authored constants.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:250:**How to roll back**: Retain the hardcoded sets as a pinned fallback through P3; if the derived predicate misbehaves, restore the constants (a one-file revert in each of the two locations).
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:264:| **Status** | Accepted (P0 remediation; promote the resolver) |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:273:The runtime front door `.opencode/bin/compiled-route.cjs` resolves its resolver from a path inside the spec tree: `compiled-route.cjs:16-21` points at `007-unified-refactor-implementation/011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs`. This repo renumbers and re-nests spec folders constantly (the memory index records repeated hyphen migrations, renumbers, and re-nests). A single such move silently breaks every compiled route to the legacy sentinel, with no observable signal. The repo's own reorganization is a latent drift engine independent of hub-config edits.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:289:**How it works**: `resolve.cjs` moves to a durable runtime path (for example `.opencode/bin/lib/`), and the shim requires it from there. The spec-tree copy becomes the authored source that is built or copied into the runtime location, so a spec renumber no longer moves the file the runtime depends on.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:300:| **Promote resolver to a runtime path (chosen)** | Removes the drift source rather than guarding it; runtime no longer depends on spec-tree layout | A small build or copy step to keep the runtime copy current | 8/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:302:| Leave as-is and document | No work now | The drift source remains and stays silent; documentation does not stop a renumber | 4/10 |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:315:- The runtime dependency graph stops reaching into the spec tree.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:324:| Runtime copy goes stale vs authored source | M | Add a freshness check to the drift-CI (P1) so a stale runtime resolver fails the same gate as a stale manifest |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:338:| 4 | **Fits Goal?** | PASS | A default-on fleet cannot rest on a resolver that a spec move can sever |
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:351:- P0: move `resolve.cjs` to a runtime path; update the shim's require; keep the authored source building or copying into place.
.opencode/specs/sk-doc/019-sk-doc-router-alignment/020-router-unification-program/007-unified-refactor-implementation/012-default-on-decision/decision-record.md:352:- P1: the drift-CI also checks the runtime resolver is current with its authored source.
