     1	---
     2	title: Manual Testing Playbook Snippet Template
     3	description: Template for per-feature scenario files stored directly under manual-testing-playbook category directories.
     4	trigger_phrases:
     5	  - "playbook snippet template"
     6	  - "per feature scenario file"
     7	  - "nine column test row"
     8	  - "scenario execution detail"
     9	importance_tier: normal
    10	contextType: general
    11	version: 1.8.0.11
    12	---
    13	
    14	# Manual Testing Playbook Snippet Template
    15	
    16	Per-feature scenario files for split manual testing playbooks. Use this template for the one-file-per-feature contract described in the main playbook template.
    17	
    18	> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed for real — not mocked, not stubbed, not classified as "unautomatable". AI agents executing these scenarios must run the actual commands, inspect real files, call real handlers, and verify real outputs. The only acceptable classifications are PASS, FAIL, or SKIP (with a specific sandbox blocker documented). "UNAUTOMATABLE" is not a valid status.
    19	
    20	---
    21	
    22	## 1. OVERVIEW
    23	
    24	Each feature file is the canonical home for full scenario execution detail. The root `manual-testing-playbook.md` stays readable by summarizing the feature and linking here, while the feature file carries the realistic user-testing context, orchestration process, 9-column test row, structured source references, and concise metadata. The file shape should intentionally mirror the Feature Catalog snippet pattern so operators can move between the catalog and the playbook without relearning the document structure.
    25	
    26	**Required uses**:
    27	- One file per feature ID
    28	- One primary 9-column scenario row per file
    29	- Frontmatter that mirrors the larger root docs (`title` + `description`)
    30	- Root playbook summary plus per-feature file cross-link
    31	- Realistic user request and orchestrator prompt
    32	- Desired user-visible outcome and execution process notes
    33	
    34	**Do not use this template for**:
    35	- General reusable prose fragments
    36	- Replacing root-level review/release-readiness or orchestration guidance
    37	- Spreading one feature across multiple primary files without a clear reason
    38	
    39	**Validator note**: The current validator checks markdown structure on the root playbook and does not recurse into category folders, so per-feature file structure needs manual review. Cross-file markdown links are verified separately by the `check-markdown-links.cjs` CI guard (fails the PR on any broken markdown link).
    40	
    41	---
    42	
    43	## 2. TEMPLATE SCAFFOLD
    44	
    45	Copy this into `manual-testing-playbook/{CATEGORY_DIR}/{FEATURE_SLUG}.md`. Both placeholder values must be kebab-case:
    46	
    47	```markdown
    48	---
    49	title: "{FEATURE_ID} -- {FEATURE_NAME}"
    50	description: "This scenario validates {FEATURE_NAME} for `{FEATURE_ID}`. It focuses on {OBJECTIVE}."
    51	stage: routing   # routing | holdout | negative — benchmark-tier grouping; carries what a numbered filename prefix used to encode
    52	# Lane C skill-benchmark fields — REQUIRED when this playbook also serves as a hub's
    53	# skill-benchmark corpus. The scenario loader SKIPS any feature file whose frontmatter
    54	# carries none of id / expected_intent / expected_resources, so a routing scenario
    55	# without them is silently absent from the D1 benchmark. Omit them for a pure
    56	# manual-testing playbook that is never scored.
    57	id: "{FEATURE_ID}"                       # stable scenario id; falls back to the filename if omitted
    58	expected_intent: "{EXPECTED_INTENT}"     # routing intent/mode the skill should select for this prompt
    59	expected_resources:                      # resource paths the correct route must load (one per line)
    60	  - "{EXPECTED_RESOURCE_PATH}"
    61	version: 1.0.0.0
    62	---
    63	
    64	# {FEATURE_ID} -- {FEATURE_NAME}
    65	
    66	This document captures the realistic user-testing contract, current behavior, execution flow, source anchors, and metadata for `{FEATURE_ID}`.
    67	
    68	---
    69	
    70	## 1. OVERVIEW
    71	
    72	This scenario validates {FEATURE_NAME} for `{FEATURE_ID}`. It focuses on {OBJECTIVE}.
    73	
    74	### Why This Matters
    75	
    76	{WHY_THIS_MATTERS}
    77	
    78	---
    79	
    80	## 2. SCENARIO CONTRACT
    81	
    82	Operators run the exact prompt and command sequence for `{FEATURE_ID}` and confirm the expected signals without contradictory evidence.
    83	
    84	- Objective: {OBJECTIVE}
    85	- Real user request: `{REAL_USER_REQUEST}`
    86	- Prompt: `{PROMPT — natural-human voice by default (e.g., "Review this auth diff for security issues"); use RCAF "As a {ROLE}, {ACTION} against {TARGET}. Verify {EXPECTED_OUTCOME}. Return {OUTPUT_FORMAT}." only when actor is an AI orchestrator. See references/prompt-voice.md.}`
    87	- Expected execution process: {EXPECTED_PROCESS}
    88	- Expected signals: {EXPECTED_SIGNALS}
    89	- Desired user-visible outcome: {DESIRED_USER_OUTCOME}
    90	- Pass/fail: PASS if {PASS_CONDITION}; FAIL if {FAIL_CONDITION}
    91	
    92	---
    93	
    94	## 3. TEST EXECUTION
    95	
    96	### Prompt
    97	
    98	- Prompt: `{PROMPT — natural-human voice by default (e.g., "Review this auth diff for security issues"); use RCAF "As a {ROLE}, {ACTION} against {TARGET}. Verify {EXPECTED_OUTCOME}. Return {OUTPUT_FORMAT}." only when actor is an AI orchestrator. See references/prompt-voice.md.}`
    99	
   100	### Commands
   101	
   102	1. `{COMMAND_1}`
   103	2. `{COMMAND_2}`
   104	
   105	### Expected
   106	
   107	{EXPECTED_SIGNALS}
   108	
   109	### Evidence
   110	
   111	{EVIDENCE_DESCRIPTION}
   112	
   113	### Pass / Fail
   114	
   115	- **Pass**: {PASS_CONDITION}
   116	- **Fail**: {FAIL_CONDITION}
   117	
   118	### Failure Triage
   119	
   120	{TRIAGE_STEPS}
   121	
   122	### Optional Supplemental Checks
   123	
   124	Use this subsection only when the feature needs a tightly scoped follow-up variant, compatibility check, or artifact note.
   125	
   126	---
   127	
   128	## 4. SOURCE FILES
   129	
   130	### Playbook Sources
   131	
   132	| File | Role |
   133	|---|---|
   134	| `manual-testing-playbook.md` | Root directory page and scenario summary |
   135	| `../../feature-catalog/{CATALOG_PATH}` | Feature-catalog source describing the implementation contract |
   136	
   137	### Implementation And Test Anchors
   138	
   139	| File | Role |
   140	|---|---|
   141	| `{IMPLEMENTATION_FILE}` | Primary implementation anchor |
   142	| `{TEST_FILE}` | Regression or validation anchor |
   143	
   144	---
   145	
   146	## 5. SOURCE METADATA
   147	
   148	- Group: {CATEGORY_NAME}
   149	- Playbook ID: {FEATURE_ID}
   150	- Canonical root source: `manual-testing-playbook.md`
   151	- Feature file path: `{CATEGORY_DIR}/{FEATURE_SLUG}.md`
   152	```
   153	
   154	### Authoring Notes
   155	
   156	- Keep the feature file aligned with the matching root summary block and feature-catalog entry.
   157	- Preserve stable feature IDs and file paths once published.
   158	- The per-feature filename is a descriptive kebab-case slug with no numeric prefix (e.g. `full-runtime-dispatch.md`, not `001-full-runtime-dispatch.md`). Ordering and benchmark tier are owned by the root index and the `stage:` frontmatter field, not the filename — the scenario loader discovers files by their frontmatter, so a numbered filename buys nothing and forces a renumber-on-insert cascade.
   159	- Set `stage:` to mark the scenario's benchmark tier: `routing` (default — a positive in-domain recall scenario), `holdout` (a generalization scenario held out of the primary set), or `negative` (an out-of-domain scenario the skill must NOT route to). This is what a numbered/holdout/negative filename token used to signal implicitly. The skill-benchmark loader treats `stage: negative` as a suppression test (negative activation), not a positive routing hit.
   160	- For a scenario that also feeds the Lane C skill-benchmark, fill `id`, `expected_intent`, and `expected_resources` in the frontmatter, and keep the exact executor prompt in the `### Prompt` block — the loader parses the prompt from that block and records a `missing-exact-prompt` warning when it is absent. `expected_resources` is the list of resource paths the correct route should load; the D1 score is measured against it.
   161	- When a feature needs extra checks, add them beneath the main row instead of creating a second primary scenario row by default.
   162	- Put feature-specific review caveats, routing notes, and isolation constraints here instead of inventing separate sidecar docs.

